- id: phase-45
  title: RAM-Mapped Canvas Buffer
  status: todo
  goal: Make the canvas grid addressable from VM RAM via STORE/LOAD
  description: 'The canvas buffer (128 rows x 32 cols = 4096 cells) currently lives in a separate Vec<u32> outside VM RAM. Map it into the VM address space at 0x8000-0x8FFF so that existing STORE and LOAD
    opcodes can read and write grid cells directly. No new opcodes needed -- just intercept the address range in the VM''s memory access path.

    '
  deliverables:
  - name: Canvas memory region constant and address mapping
    description: 'Define CANVAS_RAM_BASE = 0x8000, CANVAS_RAM_SIZE = 4096 (128*32). Document the mapping: address 0x8000 + row*32 + col corresponds to canvas_buffer[row * 32 + col]. Add to memory map docs.

      '
    status: todo
    acceptance_criteria:
    - description: CANVAS_RAM_BASE constant defined in vm.rs or main.rs
      validation: grep CANVAS_RAM_BASE src/vm.rs src/main.rs
      met: false
    - description: Memory map documentation updated in CANVAS_TEXT_SURFACE.md
      validation: grep 0x8000 docs/CANVAS_TEXT_SURFACE.md
      met: false
    tasks:
    - id: p45.d1.t1
      title: Define CANVAS_RAM_BASE and CANVAS_RAM_SIZE constants
      status: todo
      description: 'Add `pub const CANVAS_RAM_BASE: usize = 0x8000;` and `pub const CANVAS_RAM_SIZE: usize = 4096;` to vm.rs (or main.rs if canvas_buffer ownership stays there). These are the address range
        [0x8000, 0x8FFF] that maps to the canvas grid.

        '
      dependencies: []
      acceptance_criteria:
      - Constants defined and visible to both vm.rs and main.rs
      files:
      - src/vm.rs
    - id: p45.d1.t2
      title: Update CANVAS_TEXT_SURFACE.md memory map with 0x8000 range
      status: todo
      description: 'Add a row to the memory map table in CANVAS_TEXT_SURFACE.md: 0x8000-0x8FFF | 4096 | Canvas grid (RAM-mapped mirror of canvas_buffer)

        '
      dependencies:
      - p45.d1.t1
      acceptance_criteria:
      - Memory map shows 0x8000-0x8FFF as canvas region
      files:
      - docs/CANVAS_TEXT_SURFACE.md
    scope_lines: 20
    scope_files:
    - src/vm.rs
    - docs/CANVAS_TEXT_SURFACE.md
  - name: Intercept LOAD for canvas address range
    description: 'In the LOAD opcode handler (0x11 in vm.rs), when the translated physical address falls in [CANVAS_RAM_BASE, CANVAS_RAM_BASE + 4095], read from canvas_buffer instead of self.ram. The VM
      needs a reference or copy of the canvas buffer. Easiest approach: the canvas_buffer is passed to the VM (or VM holds a reference) so LOAD can index into it.

      '
    status: todo
    acceptance_criteria:
    - description: LOAD from 0x8000+row*32+col returns canvas_buffer value
      validation: 'Write test program: STORE to canvas addr, LOAD back, verify'
      met: false
    - description: LOAD from addresses outside 0x8000-0x8FFF still works normally
      validation: Existing tests pass without modification
      met: false
    tasks:
    - id: p45.d2.t1
      title: Add canvas_buffer reference to VM struct
      status: todo
      description: 'The VM struct needs access to the canvas buffer for both LOAD and STORE interception. Add a field like `pub canvas_buffer: Vec<u32>` to the VM struct (a copy that gets synced back to
        main.rs canvas_buffer each frame) OR pass it as a mutable reference through the execute method. The copy approach is simpler and avoids lifetime issues.

        '
      dependencies:
      - p45.d1.t1
      acceptance_criteria:
      - VM struct has access to canvas buffer data
      - cargo build succeeds
      files:
      - src/vm.rs
      - src/main.rs
    - id: p45.d2.t2
      title: Intercept LOAD opcode for canvas range
      status: todo
      description: 'In the LOAD handler (opcode 0x11), after page translation produces a physical address, check if it falls in [CANVAS_RAM_BASE, CANVAS_RAM_BASE + CANVAS_RAM_SIZE). If so, read from the
        canvas buffer at (addr - CANVAS_RAM_BASE) instead of self.ram[addr]. The canvas buffer index maps directly: canvas_buffer[addr - 0x8000].

        '
      dependencies:
      - p45.d2.t1
      acceptance_criteria:
      - LOAD from canvas addr returns the glyph value stored there
      - LOAD from normal RAM addr is unchanged
      files:
      - src/vm.rs
    - id: p45.d2.t3
      title: Sync canvas_buffer to VM before execution
      status: todo
      description: 'Before each frame''s VM execution, copy the current canvas_buffer contents into the VM''s canvas mirror (or set up the reference). This ensures the VM sees the latest grid state including
        human-typed text.

        '
      dependencies:
      - p45.d2.t1
      acceptance_criteria:
      - VM canvas mirror matches main.rs canvas_buffer at start of each frame
      files:
      - src/main.rs
    scope_lines: 80
    scope_files:
    - src/vm.rs
    - src/main.rs
  - name: Intercept STORE for canvas address range
    description: 'In the STORE opcode handler (0x12 in vm.rs), when the translated physical address falls in [CANVAS_RAM_BASE, CANVAS_RAM_BASE + 4095], write to canvas_buffer instead of self.ram. After
      the store, mark the canvas as dirty so the renderer picks up the change on the next frame.

      '
    status: todo
    acceptance_criteria:
    - description: STORE to 0x8000+row*32+col writes value to canvas_buffer
      validation: 'Write test: STORE 0x8000 with ''H'', see ''H'' appear on grid'
      met: false
    - description: Stored values appear as glyphs on the canvas grid
      validation: 'Visual test: program writes ASCII chars, grid shows them'
      met: false
    - description: STORE to addresses outside canvas range still works
      validation: Existing tests pass
      met: false
    tasks:
    - id: p45.d3.t1
      title: Intercept STORE opcode for canvas range
      status: todo
      description: 'In the STORE handler (opcode 0x12), after page translation, check if the address is in the canvas range. If so, write to the canvas buffer at (addr - CANVAS_RAM_BASE) instead of self.ram[addr].
        Bypass the user-mode protection for this range (canvas is not I/O).

        '
      dependencies:
      - p45.d2.t1
      acceptance_criteria:
      - STORE to canvas addr writes to canvas buffer
      - User-mode programs can write to canvas (no segfault)
      files:
      - src/vm.rs
    - id: p45.d3.t2
      title: Sync VM canvas mutations back to main canvas_buffer
      status: todo
      description: 'After each frame''s VM execution, copy any changed canvas cells from the VM''s mirror back to main.rs''s canvas_buffer. This ensures the renderer displays the VM''s writes. A simple
        full-copy each frame is fine (4096 u32 values = 16KB).

        '
      dependencies:
      - p45.d3.t1
      acceptance_criteria:
      - Changes made by VM via STORE appear on the visible canvas grid
      files:
      - src/main.rs
    - id: p45.d3.t3
      title: Handle User-mode access to canvas region
      status: todo
      description: 'The STORE handler currently blocks User-mode writes to addr >= 0xFF00. The canvas range (0x8000) is below this threshold, so User-mode should work by default. But verify and add a comment
        clarifying that canvas writes are permitted in User mode. If any page translation or protection logic would block it, add an explicit exception.

        '
      dependencies:
      - p45.d3.t1
      acceptance_criteria:
      - User-mode programs can STORE to canvas range without segfault
      files:
      - src/vm.rs
    scope_lines: 60
    scope_files:
    - src/vm.rs
    - src/main.rs
  - name: Test suite for RAM-mapped canvas
    description: 'Write tests that verify STORE/LOAD to canvas addresses work correctly. Test read-after-write, boundary conditions, interaction with normal RAM, and multi-process canvas access.

      '
    status: todo
    acceptance_criteria:
    - description: At least 5 tests covering canvas LOAD/STORE behavior
      validation: cargo test passes with new tests
      met: false
    - description: All existing tests still pass
      validation: cargo test --no-fail-fast 2>&1 | tail -5
      met: false
    tasks:
    - id: p45.d4.t1
      title: 'Test: LOAD reads canvas buffer values'
      status: todo
      description: 'Write a test that pre-fills canvas_buffer cells with known values, runs a program that LOADs from 0x8000+offset, and checks the register contains the expected value.

        '
      dependencies:
      - p45.d2.t2
      - p45.d3.t1
      acceptance_criteria:
      - Test asserts register value matches canvas cell content
      files:
      - src/vm.rs
    - id: p45.d4.t2
      title: 'Test: STORE writes appear in canvas buffer'
      status: todo
      description: 'Write a test that runs a program storing values to canvas addresses, then checks the canvas buffer contains those values.

        '
      dependencies:
      - p45.d3.t1
      acceptance_criteria:
      - Test asserts canvas_buffer has stored values after execution
      files:
      - src/vm.rs
    - id: p45.d4.t3
      title: 'Test: boundary conditions (first/last cell, row boundaries)'
      status: todo
      description: 'Test STORE/LOAD at 0x8000 (first cell), 0x8FFF (last cell), and at row boundaries (e.g. end of row 0, start of row 1). Verify no off-by-one errors.

        '
      dependencies:
      - p45.d3.t1
      acceptance_criteria:
      - All boundary addresses read/write correctly
      files:
      - src/vm.rs
    - id: p45.d4.t4
      title: 'Test: canvas access does not corrupt normal RAM'
      status: todo
      description: 'Write a test that stores to both normal RAM and canvas addresses, then verifies the normal RAM values are unchanged and the canvas values are correct. Ensures the two memory spaces don''t
        overlap.

        '
      dependencies:
      - p45.d3.t1
      acceptance_criteria:
      - RAM values unchanged after canvas writes
      - Canvas values unchanged after RAM writes
      files:
      - src/vm.rs
    - id: p45.d4.t5
      title: 'Test: page translation works with canvas addresses'
      status: todo
      description: 'Verify that LOAD/STORE to canvas addresses still go through the page translation mechanism. A process with a page table that maps 0x8000 to a different physical address should see the
