    - id: p49.d1.t3
      title: Write programs/game_of_life.asm
      description: 'Conway''s Game of Life implemented entirely in Geometry OS assembly. Uses PEEK to read the screen, POKE (or STORE to screen-mapped RAM) to write the next generation. The screen IS the
        cellular automaton. No Rust code involved in the logic -- pure pixel-driven-pixels. Initialize with a glider or blinker pattern.

        '
      dependencies:
      - p46.d1.t3
      acceptance_criteria:
      - Cells evolve according to Conway's rules
      - Gliders move, blinkers blink
      files:
      - programs/game_of_life.asm
      status: todo
    - id: p49.d1.t4
      title: Write programs/code_evolution.asm
      description: 'The crown jewel demo. A program that writes increasingly complex versions of itself to the canvas grid. Generation 0 just halts. Generation 1 writes generation 2 which adds a counter.
        Generation 2 writes generation 3 which adds a screen effect. Each generation writes its successor, compiles, and runs it. The human watches the code evolve on the grid in real time.

        '
      dependencies:
      - p48.d1.t1
      acceptance_criteria:
      - At least 3 generations of code evolution
      - Each generation visibly different from the last
      files:
      - programs/code_evolution.asm
      status: todo
    scope_lines: 300
    scope_files:
    - programs/
  - name: 'Documentation: pixel-driving-pixels patterns'
    description: 'Write a guide for building self-modifying programs. Document the patterns: canvas STORE for writing code, ASMSELF for compiling, RUNNEXT for executing, register passing between generations,
      and common pitfalls (infinite loops, corrupting your own code).

      '
    status: todo
    acceptance_criteria:
